Small garden with trees for a moment of tranquility. The Lamignon hotel was built from 1559 by Philibert Delorme, then remodeled and enlarged for the Angoul√™me family. Between 1688 and 1774, it belonged to the Lamavoine family, whose name it retained. In the 19th century, it was inhabited in particular by Alphonse Daudet, then transformed into a factory and shops. The municipality bought it in 1928 and restored it to house the Historical Library of the City of Paris in 1969. Its garden was then converted into a public square. Since 2018, this garden has paid tribute to Mark Ashton, born in 1960, gay rights activist.
